# Full Migration and Naming Rule

When updating behavior, do complete migrations. Do not keep compatibility shims.

Post-migration expectation: treat the selected architecture and contracts as steady-state and remove transition-era wording in touched canonical docs/rules.
At the end of a migration, remove migration-era filenames/labels when they are no longer semantically required.
Do not keep silent runtime fallbacks in canonical boot paths; fallback behavior, when needed, must be explicit and harness-scoped.

## 1) No Legacy Compatibility Paths

- Do not keep deprecated aliases, fallback fields, dual code paths, or "temporary" compatibility adapters.
- When a field/type/API is replaced, remove old reads/writes in the same change.
- Update save/load contracts, UI labels, docs, and callers together so the old term/path is fully gone.

## 2) Canonical Terminology First

- Before introducing a new term, search existing code/docs/rules for the canonical term already in use.
- Reuse existing nomenclature if it already fits.
- If renaming is required, pick one canonical term and apply it consistently across:
  - runtime code
  - inspectors/UI labels
  - events/contracts
  - docs/rules/reference files

## 3) Done Criteria

- No stale references to replaced terms in code paths touched by the change.
- No contradictory terminology between `src/**`, `.cursor/rules/**`, `llms.txt`, and `docs/**` / `design/**`.
- No "legacy"/"deprecated compatibility" comments left behind unless explicitly requested.
- Treat `.cursor/plans/**` as historical planning artifacts, not canonical contracts.
